04539nam a22005775i 9780822383789DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223837897 a10.1515/97808223837892doi  a(DE-B1597)554111  a(OCoLC)1226678975  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.3/09832211 aTinsman, Heidi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPartners in Conflict :bThe Politics of Gender, Sexuality, and Labor in the Chilean Agrarian Reform, 1950–1973 /cHeidi Tinsman; ed. by Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (389 p.) :b25 b&w photos, 22 tables, 2 maps, 6 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies : 4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps and Tables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Patrón and Peón -- t2 Binding Ties -- t3 Making Men -- t4 Promoting Gender Mutualism -- t5 Struggling for Land -- t6 Revolutionizing Women -- t7 Coming Apart -- tEpilogue: 1973–1988 -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPartners in Conflict examines the importance of sexuality and gender to rural labor and agrarian politics during the last days of Chile’s latifundia system of traditional landed estates and throughout the governments of Eduardo Frei and Salvador Allende. Heidi Tinsman analyzes differences between men’s and women’s participation in Chile’s Agrarian Reform movement and considers how conflicts over gender and sexuality shape the contours of working-class struggles and national politics.Tinsman restores women to a scholarly narrative that has been almost exclusively about men, recounting the centrality of women’s labor to the pre-Agrarian Reform world of the hacienda during the 1950s and recovering women’s critical roles in union struggles and land occupations during the Agrarian Reform itself. Providing a theoretical framework for understanding why the Agrarian Reform ultimately empowered men more than women, Tinsman argues that women were marginalized not because the Agrarian Reform ignored women but because, under both the Frei and Allende governments, it promoted the male-headed household as the cornerstone of a new society. Although this emphasis on gender cooperation stressed that men should have more respect for their wives and funneled unprecedented amounts of resources into women’s hands, the reform defined men as its protagonists and affirmed their authority over women.This is the first monographic social history of Chile’s Agrarian Reform in either English or Spanish, and the first historical work to make sexuality and gender central to the analysis of the reforms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLand reformzChilexHistoryy20th century. 0aPeasantszChilexHistoryy20th century. 0aSex rolezChilexHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383789zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822383789/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles